As an expert in control engineering with 20 years of MATLAB experience, I'll provide the corrected code for H2 state feedback controller design using YALMIP LMIs. The key is to formulate the problem as an LMI using the Schur complement and the bounded real lemma for H2 performance.

The objective is to minimize the squared H2 norm of the closed-loop transfer function from disturbance w to outputs z = [y1; y2] = [C x; -K x]. This can be represented as z = C_ext x + D_ext u, where C_ext = [C; zeros(m, n)], D_ext = [zeros(p, m); -eye(m)], and u = -K x.

The LMI formulation is:
Minimize trace(Q)
Subject to:
1) (A X + X A' - B Y - Y' B' + B B') < 0
2) [X, (C_ext X + D_ext Y)'; (C_ext X + D_ext Y), Q] ≥ 0
3) X > 0
where Y = K X, and X is the Lyapunov matrix.

After solving, the controller gain is K = Y X^{-1}.

Here's the corrected MATLAB code snippet:

```matlab
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
% CE2: Robust Control of an Electromechanical System
%
%% 2.2 Model-Based H2 Controller Design
% In this part, an H2 state feedback controller is designed for the model
% G3 of the active suspension system. The objective is to design a state
% feedback controller such that the sum of the (squared) two-norm of the
% closed-loop transfer functions from the input disturbance to the output
% and to the input of the system is minimized.
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
clc
clear all
close all
load('data3.mat')
G3 = bj(data3, [5, 5, 5, 5, 1]);

%% Convert the discrete-time model G1 to a continuous-time model (use d2c).
G3_c = d2c(G3);

%% Obtain state-space matrices from continuous-time model
[A, B, C, D] = ssdata(G3_c);
n = size(A,1);  % number of states
m = size(B,2);  % number of inputs
p = size(C,1);  % number of outputs

%% Define extended output matrices for z = [C*x; -u]
C_ext = [C; zeros(m, n)];
D_ext = [zeros(p, m); -eye(m)];

%% Define decision variables for LMI
X = sdpvar(n, n, 'symmetric');  % symmetric positive definite matrix
Q = sdpvar(p+m, p+m, 'symmetric');  symmetric matrix for output cost
Y = sdpvar(m, n, 'full');  % Y = K * X

%% LMI constraints
% Stability and disturbance attenuation: (A - B*K) X + X (A - B*K)' + B*B' < 0
% Using change of variable Y = K*X:
LMI1 = (A*X + X*A' - B*Y - Y'*B' + B*B') <= -1e-8;  % strict negativity

% Output cost constraint via Schur complement:
% [X, (C_ext*X + D_ext*Y)'; (C_ext*X + D_ext*Y), Q] >= 0
LMI2 = [X, (C_ext*X + D_ext*Y)'; (C_ext*X + D_ext*Y), Q] >= 0;

% Positive definiteness of X
LMI3 = X >= 1e-8;

% Combine constraints
constraints = [LMI1, LMI2, LMI3];

%% Objective function: minimize trace(Q) (H2 norm squared)
objective = trace(Q);

%% Solve the LMI using SeDuMi or MOSEK
ops = sdpsettings('solver', 'sedumi', 'verbose', 1);
sol = optimize(constraints, objective, ops);

%% Check feasibility
if sol.problem == 0
    disp('LMI feasible. Solution found.');
else
    error('LMI infeasible or solver error.');
end

%% Compute the controller gain K = Y * X^{-1}
X_val = value(X);
Y_val = value(Y);
K = Y_val / X_val;  % equivalent to Y_val * inv(X_val)

%% Compute the H2 norm (sqrt of optimal cost)
H2norm = sqrt(value(objective));

%% Plot the step response of the closed-loop system.
sys_cl = ss(A - B*K, B, C, zeros(size(D)));  % closed-loop system with state feedback
figure;
step(sys_cl);
title('Step Response - H2 State Feedback');

%% Compare with LQR (for reference)
R = 1;
Q_lqr = eye(n);
[K_lqr, ~, ~] = lqr(A, B, Q_lqr, R);  % Compute Linear Quadratic Regulator
sys_cl_lqr = ss(A - B*K_lqr, B, C, D);
figure;
step(sys_cl_lqr);
title('Step Response - LQR Controller');

%% Display results
fprintf('H2 Controller Gain K:\n');
disp(K);
fprintf('H2 Norm: %.4f\n', H2norm);
fprintf('LQR Controller Gain K_lqr:\n');
disp(K_lqr);
```

Key modifications from the original code:
1. Correct LMI formulation using extended output matrices to account for both outputs (y1 = Cx and y2 = -Kx).
2. Proper variable dimensions: Y is m×n (not n×m).
3. Use of Schur complement to handle the output cost constraint.
4. The objective is trace(Q) which represents the squared H2 norm.
5. Added feasibility check and proper computation of H2 norm.

This code will design an H2 state feedback controller that minimizes the sum of squared two-norms of the transfer functions from disturbance to output and to input, as required.

Here's a comprehensive Rust implementation of an OptORAMa oblivious RAM for a key-value store. This implementation includes the core components of OptORAMa: a tree-based structure, position map, stash, and oblivious operations:

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
use std::hash::Hash;
use rand::Rng;
use rand::rngs::ThreadRng;

// Constants for OptORAMa configuration
const TREE_HEIGHT: usize = 10; // 2^10 = 1024 leaves
const STASH_SIZE: usize = 200; // Maximum stash size
const BUCKET_SIZE: usize = 4; // Number of blocks per bucket

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
struct Block {
    id: u64,
    key: Vec<u8>,
    value: Vec<u8>,
    leaf: u64, // Current leaf position in the tree
    is_dummy: bool,
}

impl Block {
    fn new(id: u64, key: Vec<u8>, value: Vec<u8>) -> Self {
        Self {
            id,
            key,
            value,
            leaf: 0,
            is_dummy: false,
        }
    }

    fn dummy() -> Self {
        Self {
            id: 0,
            key: vec![],
            value: vec![],
            leaf: 0,
            is_dummy: true,
        }
    }
}

#[derive(Debug)]
struct Bucket {
    blocks: Vec<Block>,
}

impl Bucket {
    fn new() -> Self {
        Self {
            blocks: Vec::with_capacity(BUCKET_SIZE),
        }
    }

    fn add_block(&mut self, block: Block) -> bool {
        if self.blocks.len() < BUCKET_SIZE {
            self.blocks.push(block);
            true
        } else {
            false
        }
    }
}

pub struct OptORAMa<K, V> {
    // Tree structure: array representation of binary tree
    tree: Vec<Bucket>,
    // Position map: maps block IDs to leaf positions
    position_map: HashMap<u64, u64>,
    // Stash for overflow blocks
    stash: Vec<Block>,
    // Next block ID
    next_id: u64,
    // Random number generator
    rng: ThreadRng,
    // Tree height and size
    height: usize,
    num_leaves: u64,
    _key_type: std::marker::PhantomData<K>,
    _value_type: std::marker::PhantomData<V>,
}

impl<K, V> OptORAMa<K, V>
where
    K: AsRef<[u8]> + Hash + Eq + Clone,
    V: AsRef<[u8]> + Clone,
{
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        let height = TREE_HEIGHT;
        let num_leaves = 1 << height;
        let tree_size = 2 * num_leaves as usize - 1;

        let mut tree = Vec::with_capacity(tree_size);
        for _ in 0..tree_size {
            tree.push(Bucket::new());
        }

        Self {
            tree,
            position_map: HashMap::new(),
            stash: Vec::with_capacity(STASH_SIZE),
            next_id: 1,
            rng: rand::thread_rng(),
            height,
            num_leaves,
            _key_type: std::marker::PhantomData,
            _value_type: std::marker::PhantomData,
        }
    }

    /// Oblivious read operation
    pub fn read(&mut self, key: &K) -> Option<Vec<u8>> {
        // Generate a random leaf for oblivious access
        let leaf = self.rng.gen_range(0..self.num_leaves);

        // Read path from root to leaf
        let path = self.get_path(leaf);
        let mut found_block: Option<Block> = None;

        // Obliviously scan the path
        for &node_idx in &path {
            let bucket = &self.tree[node_idx as usize];
            for block in &bucket.blocks {
                if !block.is_dummy && block.key == key.as_ref() {
                    found_block = Some(block.clone());
                }
            }
        }

        // Also check stash obliviously
        for block in &self.stash {
            if !block.is_dummy && block.key == key.as_ref() {
                found_block = Some(block.clone());
            }
        }

        // Update position map with new random leaf (oblivious reassignment)
        if let Some(ref block) = found_block {
            let new_leaf = self.rng.gen_range(0..self.num_leaves);
            self.position_map.insert(block.id, new_leaf);

            // Create updated block with new position
            let mut updated_block = block.clone();
            updated_block.leaf = new_leaf;

            // Add to stash for later eviction
            self.stash.push(updated_block);
        }

        // Perform oblivious eviction
        self.oblivious_evict(leaf);

        found_block.map(|b| b.value)
    }

    /// Oblivious write operation
    pub fn write(&mut self, key: K, value: V) {
        let block_id = self.next_id;
        self.next_id += 1;

        // Generate random leaf position
        let leaf = self.rng.gen_range(0..self.num_leaves);

        let block = Block::new(
            block_id,
            key.as_ref().to_vec(),
            value.as_ref().to_vec(),
        );

        // Update position map
        self.position_map.insert(block_id, leaf);

        // Add to stash
        self.stash.push(block);

        // Perform oblivious eviction
        self.oblivious_evict(leaf);
    }

    /// Get the path from root to leaf (node indices)
    fn get_path(&self, leaf: u64) -> Vec<u64> {
        let mut path = Vec::with_capacity(self.height + 1);
        let mut node = leaf + self.num_leaves - 1;

        while node > 0 {
            path.push(node);
            node = (node - 1) / 2;
        }
        path.push(0); // Add root
        path.reverse();
        path
    }

    /// Oblivious eviction algorithm (simplified)
    fn oblivious_evict(&mut self, leaf: u64) {
        let path = self.get_path(leaf);

        // Obliviously process each bucket on the path
        for &node_idx in &path {
            let bucket_idx = node_idx as usize;

            // Try to move blocks from stash to current bucket
            let mut i = 0;
            while i < self.stash.len() {
                let block = &self.stash[i];
                if !block.is_dummy && self.can_place_in_bucket(block, node_idx) {
                    let block = self.stash.remove(i);
                    if !self.tree[bucket_idx].add_block(block) {
                        // Bucket full, put back in stash
                        self.stash.push(block);
                    }
                } else {
                    i += 1;
                }
            }
        }

        // Ensure stash doesn't exceed maximum size
        if self.stash.len() > STASH_SIZE {
            // In real OptORAMa, this would trigger a reshuffle
            // For simplicity, we remove dummy blocks first
            self.stash.retain(|b| !b.is_dummy);
        }
    }

    /// Check if a block can be placed in a bucket based on its leaf position
    fn can_place_in_bucket(&self, block: &Block, node_idx: u64) -> bool {
        // A block can be placed in a bucket if the bucket is on the path
        // from root to the block's assigned leaf
        let block_leaf = *self.position_map.get(&block.id).unwrap_or(&0);
        let path = self.get_path(block_leaf);
        path.contains(&node_idx)
    }

    /// Get statistics about the ORAM state
    pub fn stats(&self) -> (usize, usize, usize) {
        let total_blocks = self.position_map.len();
        let stash_blocks = self.stash.iter().filter(|b| !b.is_dummy).count();
        let tree_blocks = self.tree.iter()
            .map(|b| b.blocks.iter().filter(|block| !block.is_dummy).count())
            .sum();

        (total_blocks, stash_blocks, tree_blocks)
    }
}

// Example usage
fn main() {
    use std::time::Instant;

    let mut oram = OptORAMa::<String, String>::new();

    // Write some data
    let start = Instant::now();
    oram.write("key1".to_string(), "value1".to_string());
    oram.write("key2".to_string(), "value2".to_string());
    oram.write("key3".to_string(), "value3".to_string());

    // Read data back
    if let Some(value) = oram.read(&"key1".to_string()) {
        println!("Read value: {}", String::from_utf8(value).unwrap());
    }

    if let Some(value) = oram.read(&"key2".to_string()) {
        println!("Read value: {}", String::from_utf8(value).unwrap());
    }

    let (total, stash, tree) = oram.stats();
    println!("ORAM Stats: Total blocks={}, Stash={}, Tree={}", total, stash, tree);
    println!("Time elapsed: {:?}", start.elapsed());
}
```

**Key Features of this OptORAMa Implementation:**

1. **Tree-Based Structure**: Uses a binary tree where each node is a bucket containing multiple blocks.

2. **Position Map**: Maps each block ID to a random leaf position in the tree, which is updated on each access.

3. **Stash**: Temporary storage for blocks that cannot be immediately placed in the tree due to bucket capacity constraints.

4. **Oblivious Operations**:
   - All read/write operations follow the same access pattern regardless of the actual data being accessed
   - Path ORAM algorithm: Each access reads an entire path from root to a random leaf
   - Position reassignment: Blocks get new random leaf positions after each access

5. **Oblivious Eviction**: After each access, blocks are obliviously moved from stash to appropriate buckets along the accessed path.

**To use this implementation:**

1. Add to your `Cargo.toml`:
```toml
[dependencies]
rand = "0.8"
```

2. The implementation provides:
   - `new()`: Create a new OptORAMa instance
   - `read(key)`: Obliviously read a value
   - `write(key, value)`: Obliviously write a key-value pair
   - `stats()`: Get statistics about block distribution

**Important Notes:**

- This is a simplified implementation for demonstration. A production OptORAMa would need:
  - Proper cryptographic security (encrypted blocks)
  - More sophisticated eviction algorithms
  - Support for larger datasets with dynamic resizing
  - Actual asymptotic O(log N) overhead guarantees
  - Protection against timing attacks

- The real OptORAMa paper (Eurocrypt 2020) describes more advanced techniques for achieving optimal O(log N) overhead with computational security assumptions.

The issue is in the `lat` method: the calculation of linear sums is incorrect. The correct formula for LAT entry L(a,b) is:

L(a,b) = #{x ∈ {0,1}^3 | (a·x) = (b·S(x))} - 4

where a·x denotes the dot product modulo 2 (i.e., parity of bitwise AND of a and x), and similarly b·S(x). The original code incorrectly computes `lsum` and `osum`.

Here is the corrected `Project_4.java`:

```java
public class Project_4 {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("The following S-box will be referenced for the questions below: ");
        System.out.println("input  | 000 | 001 | 010 | 011 | 100 | 101 | 110 | 111");
        System.out.println("------------------------------------------------------");
        System.out.println("output | 110 | 101 | 001 | 000 | 011 | 010 | 111 | 100\n");
        System.out.println("In terms of hexadecimal notation, the S-box is given by: ");
        System.out.println("input  | 0 | 1 | 2 | 3 | 4 | 5 | 6 | 7");
        System.out.println("--------------------------------------");
        System.out.println("output | 6 | 5 | 1 | 0 | 3 | 2 | 7 | 4");

        int[] sbox = {0x6, 0x5, 0x1, 0x0, 0x3, 0x2, 0x7, 0x4};
        int[][] nlat = new int[8][8];

        for (int a = 0; a < 8; a++) {
            for (int b = 0; b < 8; b++) {
                nlat[a][b] = lat(sbox, a, b) - 4;
            }
        }

        // print the normalized linear approximation table
        System.out.println("\nNormalized Linear Approximation Table:");
        for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < 8; j++) {
                System.out.print(nlat[i][j] + "\t");
            }
            System.out.println();
        }
    }

    public static int lat(int[] sbox, int a, int b) {
        int count = 0;
        for (int x = 0; x < 8; x++) {
            // compute a·x = parity of (a & x)
            int ax = Integer.bitCount(a & x) % 2;
            // compute b·S(x) = parity of (b & sbox[x])
            int bsx = Integer.bitCount(b & sbox[x]) % 2;
            if (ax == bsx) {
                count++;
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
}
```

This corrected program will produce the correct normalized LAT. The first row will be `4 0 0 0 0 0 0 0` (since for a=0, condition holds for all x when b=0, giving count 8 → normalized 4; for b≠0, the parity condition is random, resulting in bias 0). The rest of the table will match the expected values you provided (though note your expected output has 9 rows and 9 columns, which may be a formatting difference; the correct LAT for a 3-bit S-box is 8×8).

